Vercel Deployment Guide – Free Tier (PostgreSQL)

Project: budolshap (Next.js – App Router)
Date: 2025‑11‑23

---

1. Prerequisites
   • Git installed on Windows.
   • Node.js (v18+) and npm (or Yarn).
   • A GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket account (Vercel pulls code from a Git repo).
   • A Vercel account (free tier).
   • A free PostgreSQL instance (Neon, Supabase, or Railway).

2. Create a free PostgreSQL instance (Neon example)
   1. Sign‑up at https://neon.tech.
   2. Click “New Project” → “Create a new PostgreSQL instance”.
   3. Name it (e.g., budolshap‑dev) and create.
   4. Copy the connection string, e.g.:
      postgresql://USER:PASS@HOST:5432/DB?sslmode=require

3. Wire the DB into the Next.js app (Prisma)
   • Add the connection string to .env.local (do NOT commit):
        DATABASE_URL="postgresql://USER:PASS@HOST:5432/DB?sslmode=require"
   • Verify locally:
        npm install
        npx prisma migrate dev --name init
   • Ensure prisma/schema.prisma contains:
        datasource db { provider = "postgresql" url = env("DATABASE_URL") }

4. Prepare the repository for Vercel
   • git init (if not already)
   • Create .gitignore (node_modules/, .next/, .env.local, .DS_Store)
   • git add . ; git commit -m "Initial commit – ready for Vercel with Postgres"
   • Push to GitHub (or other):
        git remote add origin https://github.com/<USER>/budolshap.git
        git branch -M main
        git push -u origin main
   • Ensure package.json scripts include:
        "dev": "next dev",
        "build": "next build",
        "start": "next start",
        "postinstall": "prisma generate && prisma migrate deploy"
   • Commit the change.

5. Create the Vercel project
   1. Log in to https://vercel.com.
   2. New Project → Import Git Repository → select the repo.
   3. Vercel auto‑detects Next.js (Framework Preset: Next.js, Build Command: npm run build, Output Directory: .next).
   4. Deploy (first deploy will fail until env var is added).

6. Add DATABASE_URL env var on Vercel
   • Project Settings → Environment Variables → Add:
        Key: DATABASE_URL
        Value: (paste the Neon connection string)
        Environment: Production (and optionally Preview)
   • Save – Vercel will redeploy.

7. Prisma migrations on Vercel
   • Because of the postinstall script, every deployment runs:
        prisma generate && prisma migrate deploy
   • If you prefer a manual one‑off migration, use Vercel CLI:
        npm i -g vercel
        vercel login
        vercel exec -- npx prisma migrate deploy

8. Verify the live deployment
   • Open https://<project>.vercel.app
   • Test a feature that hits the DB (e.g., view products, place an order).
   • If data persists, the DB connection works.

9. Troubleshooting
   • 404 on API routes – check DATABASE_URL is correct and includes ?sslmode=require.
   • Build fails – missing module – clear Vercel build cache and redeploy.
   • Prisma migration pending – ensure postinstall script is present or run manual migration.
   • Env var not found – add it to Production environment.

10. Optional: Custom domain
    • Project Settings → Domains → Add your domain (e.g., www.myshop.com).
    • Follow DNS instructions (CNAME to cname.vercel-dns.com or A record to Vercel IPs).
    • After propagation, the domain points to your Vercel deployment.

11. Monitor free‑tier limits (Vercel)
    • Build minutes: 100 hrs/month
    • Serverless execution: 125 k GB‑seconds/month
    • Bandwidth: 100 GB/month
    • Concurrent builds: 1
    • Custom domains: Unlimited

12. Next steps
    • Enable Vercel Analytics.
    • Set up Preview Deployments for PR testing.
    • Explore Edge Functions for ultra‑low‑latency APIs.
    • Add a read‑only replica if you need heavy read scaling.

---

End of guide
